<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 93 / International Company News: Banamex poised to offer Dollars
320m of MTNs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANCO Nacional de Mexico, (Banamex), Mexico's largest bank, is poised to
offer 1bn pesos (Dollars 320m) of medium-term notes in the international
capital markets. It will be the first peso-denominated Euronote offering by
a Mexican company since Mexico's return to international debt markets in
1989.
Banamex's existing peso debt is rated A grade by Standard &amp; Poor's. The
issue will enable Banamex to fund peso loans at a lower rate than that
available in Mexico. The notes can be issued with maturities from 30 days to
10 years. The offering is expected to be followed by other Mexican companies
keen to sell peso-denominated debt to foreign investors.
The Mexican government has tapped foreign interest in high-yielding peso
treasury bonds, but Mexican companies have up to now brought in foreign
funds mainly by offering dollar-denominated debt.
