<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUL 93 / Surveyors warn of 'suicidal' prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTENSE competition is forcing construction prices down to suicidal levels,
the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors warned yesterday, Andrew Taylor
writes.
It said that contractors' tender prices had fallen 3 per cent in the first
three months of this year - the lowest level since 1986. But contractors'
construction costs were expected to rise 5.5 per cent in the next 24 months.
The institution added that spare capacity among contractors meant that
tender prices were unlikely to rise until well into next year. Its tender
price index had fallen 25 per cent since 1989.
